Will Chase Young be an All-Pro Player: A Python Tutorial¶

Background¶

As a fan of the NFL's Washington Football Team, I have become accustomed to disappointment. Year after year, we have been let down by the team. Washington has simply not been a place for greatness since the early 1990s. However, in 2020, fans were given a ray of hope. His name was Chase Young. The rookie defensive lineman exploded onto the NFL scene, racking up highlights all over the field and earning Defensive Rookie of the Year honors. Now people are calling him an early contender for overall Defensive Player of the Year for the 2021 season. As a fan, all this hype gets me very excited, but as a Washington fan, I know better than to assume these lofty projections will actually come true. In order to properly weigh the validity of these expectations, we will analyze NFL defensive player statistics, and discover trends to project whether a player will become a star based on their play in seasons past.

In sum, the goal of this tutorial is to predict Chase Young's statistics for his best season, then see if those statistics would be good enough to earn him all-pro honors. Formally, our null hypothesis is that Chase Young will never be an all-pro player. Let's hope we prove that wrong.

Libraries¶

For many python projects, it helps to import libraries of already written python objects and methods. For this project, we will use several libraries to help us in managing and plotting data. BeautifulSoup and requests will help us pull data from the internet, pandas and numpy will help with creating and managing the data tables, and pyplot makes plotting the data easier.

Part 1: Gather Data¶

The Data¶

We will use data collected by Pro Football Reference. The site keeps detailed records of game, season, and player stats from most of the league's 100 year existance. We will focus on defensive player statistics from the 2006-2020 seasons. We are starting at 2006 because that was the year the NFL started recording a new statistic, "Quarterback Hits," which may help us better predict the success of pass rushers.

Unfortunately, Pro Football Reference releases its information in yearly tables, so we will need to pull data for each year individually, then merge them into one single table to use for the rest of the tutorial. First, we will go through the step-by-step process of scraping the data from the site and formatting it to fit our needs for just the 2006 season, then we will loop through the rest of the years to complete our table.

Source: https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2020/defense.htm

Step 1: Data Scraping¶

First, we pull the data from the html page using requests. We then use BeautifulSoup to format the scraped data. Finally, we turn the data into a pandas DataFrame.

b) Keep only useful data¶

Our table is ready to be modified now that the columns are properly formatted. First, we will start erasing data that is not important to us. Our focus is on projecting the success of Chase Young, so we only need to look at players who do what he does on the field. That means we can erase every player that is not a pass rusher (Chase Young is a pass rusher).

First, take a look at the positions stored in the table. One thing stands out: some are uppercase, and some are lowercase. Before we can erase the positions we don't want, we need to make the format universal. To do this, set all the strings stored in the column to uppercase.

print(table['Pos'].unique())

table['Pos'] = [str(pos).upper() for pos in table['Pos']]

Now that the positions are universally formatted, we can identify and pull the correct positions from the table. Positions that typically focus on rushing the passer are: Oustide Linebackers (OLB), Defensive Ends (LB), and Defensive Tackles (DT).

Make a list of all positions stored in the table fitting one of those titles.

In [10]:
positions = []
for pos in table['Pos'].unique():
    if  "DT" in pos or "OLB" in pos or "DE" in pos:
        positions.append(pos)

Now that we are cutting the table down to just the positions we care about, we will start using a new table: "linemen." We are going iterate through the list of acceptable positions we just made and put all rows from the original table that match these positions into the new linemen table.

In [11]:
linemen = table.loc[table['Pos'] == positions[0]]
for i in range(1, len(positions)):
    linemen = linemen.append(table.loc[table['Pos'] == positions[i]])

Just as we only want to look at players comparable to Chase Young, we also only want to look at the statistics that are important to players of his position. For our study, we will use age, position, games started, sacks, QB hits, and total tackles. We will also keep player names to help us identify Chase Young in future plots.

In [12]:
linemen = linemen[['Player','Age','Pos','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk','Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']]

Another wrinkle in the formatting of the data is that the numbers stored in the frame are not actually numbers. They're strings! To fix this, we can call the to_numeric function on all comumns that should hold numbers to convert them to usable numbers.

In [13]:
linemen[['Age','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk','Tackles_Comb',
         'Tackles_QBHits']] = linemen[['Age','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk',
                                       'Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']].apply(pd.to_numeric)

Our final piece in cutting down the table is to make sure we are looking at players who regularly see the field. We do not want our averages and/or projectections to be weighed down by someone who only played one snap all season long. Therefore, we are only going to keep data for players that started at least half of the games in a season. Since a season is 16 games long, they needed to have played for at least 8 games.

In [14]:
linemen = linemen.loc[linemen['Games_GS'] >= 8]
linemen = linemen.reset_index(drop=True)

c) Standardize the data¶

There is a simple truth to the numbers we are looking at: a player who played 8 games will have a lower number in any catagory to an equally-skilled player who played 16. Therefore we need to standardize the numbers in the columns by making them all projections for how a 16 game season would have looked for these players. We will do this by multiplying each value by (16 / games played) for each row.

In [15]:
standardized_sacks = []
standardized_tackles = []
standardized_QB_hits = []
for i in range(len(linemen)):
    standardized_sacks.append(linemen.at[i, 'Sk'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
    standardized_tackles.append(linemen.at[i, 'Tackles_Comb'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
    standardized_QB_hits.append(linemen.at[i, 'Tackles_QBHits'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
    
linemen['Sk'] = standardized_sacks
linemen['Tackles_Comb'] = standardized_tackles
linemen['Tackles_QBHits'] = standardized_QB_hits

We can now drop the games played and started columns.

In [16]:
linemen = linemen.drop(columns=['Games_G','Games_GS'])

d) Add information to the table¶

Our table is looking good! Now that the information already stored is properly formatted, we can start adding columns to hold details on the rows that are not already stored in a reachable format. The information we want to add is: the year the row's data occurred, whether the player in the row made the pro bowl, and whether the player was an "all-pro" that season (an all-pro is a player deemed the very best at their position for the season).

The year is whatever year's data we are looking at, so all rows get "2006" for that column. Pro bowl and all pro designations are actually stored in the table already, under the Player column. If a player's name has an "*" next to it, they made the pro bowl. If there is a "+," then they were an all-pro.

Iterate through each row in the column, recording in lists what should be placed in the respective columns for each row (for year, it's the year; for pro bowl and all-pro, it's a "1" if they are, and a "0" otherwise), then add these lists as columns in the DataFrame.

In [17]:
year_list = []
made_pro_bowl = []
made_all_pro = []
for i in range(len(linemen)):
    year_list.append(2006)
    if "*" in linemen.at[i, 'Player']:
        made_pro_bowl.append(1)
    else:
        made_pro_bowl.append(0)
    
    if "+" in linemen.at[i, 'Player']:
        made_all_pro.append(1)
    else:
        made_all_pro.append(0)

f) Repeat steps a-d for the 2007-2020 data¶

As the above table is only the data for one year, we will need to do all the work over again for the other years. Each time we complete a cycle, the DataFrame for the current year will be appended to the master table, player_stats.

In [21]:
for cur_year in range(2007,2021):
    # Step a)
    url = "https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/" + str(cur_year) + "/defense.htm"
    page = reqs.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.text)
    soup_table = soup.findAll('table')[0]
    table = pd.read_html(str(soup_table))[0]
    
    # Step b)
    table.index = list(table.index)
    table.columns = list(table.columns)
    table.columns = [name[1] if "Unnamed" in name[0] else name[0] + "_" + name[1] for name in table.columns]
    table['Pos'] = [str(pos).upper() for pos in table['Pos']]
    
    linemen = table.loc[table['Pos'] == positions[0]]
    for i in range(1, len(positions)):
        linemen = linemen.append(table.loc[table['Pos'] == positions[i]])
        
    linemen = linemen[['Player','Age','Pos','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk','Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']]
    
    linemen[['Age','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk','Tackles_Comb',
         'Tackles_QBHits']] = linemen[['Age','Games_G','Games_GS','Sk',
                                       'Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']].apply(pd.to_numeric)

    linemen = linemen.loc[linemen['Games_GS'] >= 8]
    linemen = linemen.reset_index(drop=True)
    
    # Step c)
    standardized_sacks = []
    standardized_tackles = []
    standardized_QB_hits = []
    for i in range(len(linemen)):
        standardized_sacks.append(linemen.at[i, 'Sk'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
        standardized_tackles.append(linemen.at[i, 'Tackles_Comb'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
        standardized_QB_hits.append(linemen.at[i, 'Tackles_QBHits'] * (16 / linemen.at[i, 'Games_G']))
    
    linemen['Sk'] = standardized_sacks
    linemen['Tackles_Comb'] = standardized_tackles
    linemen['Tackles_QBHits'] = standardized_QB_hits
    linemen = linemen.drop(columns=['Games_G','Games_GS'])
    
    # Step d)
    year_list = []
    made_pro_bowl = []
    made_all_pro = []
    for i in range(len(linemen)):
        year_list.append(cur_year)
        if "*" in linemen.at[i, 'Player']:
            made_pro_bowl.append(1)
        else:
            made_pro_bowl.append(0)
    
        if "+" in linemen.at[i, 'Player']:
            made_all_pro.append(1)
        else:
            made_all_pro.append(0)
            
    linemen['year'] = year_list
    linemen['made_pro_bowl'] = made_pro_bowl
    linemen['made_all_pro'] = made_all_pro
    
    linemen['Player'] = [cur_name.split("*")[0].strip() for cur_name in linemen['Player']]
    linemen['Player'] = [cur_name.split("+")[0].strip() for cur_name in linemen['Player']]

    # Step e)
    player_stats = player_stats.append(linemen)

Finished!¶

The table is now complete. All relevant players and stats from 2006-2007 are stored and formatted for our use. We can now move on to the analyzing portion of the expirement.

For a final reference, here are the descriptions of each column:

  • Player: Player name
  • Age: Age of the player
  • Pos: Player position
  • Sk: Number of sacks recorded by player
  • Tackles_Comb: Total number of tackles by the player
  • Tackles_QBHits: Number of times the defender made contact with the Quarterback during a passing play
  • Year: Year the data occurred
  • made_pro_bowl: 1 if the player made the pro bowl in given season, 0 otherwise
  • made_all_pro: 1 if the player made the all-pro team in given season, 0 otherwise

Step 1: Observations By Position¶

The first category we are going to observe is Position type. While all positions are pass-rushing groups, we do not know if the data we are looking at varies strongly between the different types of pass rushers. To determine any difference in the distribution of values for sacks, QB hits, and total tackles between the positions, we will use a violin plot. A violin plot is an object where the wider its body, the higher the number of values at that spot in the y-axis. It also tells us the mean, max, and min of the data.

a) Isolate important data¶

For this section we only need the data regarding our independent variable (position), and our dependent variables (Sacks, tackles, and QB hits).

In [25]:
position_stats = player_stats[['Pos','Sk','Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']]

b) Reformat data to prepare for plotting¶

In order to create violin plots, our data needs to be formatted to fit the required inputs. To do so, we must follow these steps:

  1. Group the data by position.
  2. Convert each column in the DataFrame into lists of lists, where each sublist is the column for its corresponding position group.
In [26]:
# Step 1: Group the data by position
position_data = position_stats.groupby('Pos')
In [27]:
# Step 2: Convert each column in the DataFrame into lists of lists, 
# where each sublist is the column for its corresponding position group

# Initializing the rows of rows
Sacks_by_pos = []
Tackles_by_pos = []
QB_hits_by_pos = []
positions = []

# Loop through each group and add each column to the corresponding list of lists
for pos, group in position_data:
    positions.append(pos)
    Sacks_by_pos.append([x for x in group['Sk'].tolist() if str(x) != 'nan'])
    Tackles_by_pos.append([x for x in group['Tackles_Comb'].tolist() if str(x) != 'nan'])
    QB_hits_by_pos.append([x for x in group['Tackles_QBHits'].tolist() if str(x) != 'nan'])

# Put these lists of lists in one big list to make it easy to call them in a loop for plotting
stats_by_pos = [Sacks_by_pos,Tackles_by_pos,QB_hits_by_pos]
stat_names = ["Sacks","Total Tackles","QB Hits"]

c) Plot data¶

Now we create our plots. We are going to create one plot for each of our three dependent variables, so we will loop through the plot-making steps three times.

In [28]:
for i in range(3):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(30, 10))
    cur_stat = stat_names[i]
    
    X = positions
    Y = stats_by_pos[i]
    title = cur_stat + " by Position, 2006-2020"
    
    ax.violinplot(Y,showmeans=True)
    ax.set_xlabel("Position",fontsize=25)
    ax.set_ylabel(cur_stat,fontsize=25)
    ax.set_title(title,fontsize=40)
    plt.grid(axis='y')
    
    ax.set_xticks(np.arange(1, len(positions) + 1))
    ax.set_xticklabels(positions)

d) Analysis¶

The plots above show that two position groups stood out from the rest: left and right defensive tackles. In all three categories, their mean values and largest points of concentration were much lower than the other positions. As Chase Young is a defensive end, and we want our predictive models to be most accurate for him specifically, we should remove defensive tackles from our data, as they would bring down the value of any model we would make in the future.

In [29]:
player_stats = player_stats[player_stats.Pos != "RDT"]
player_stats = player_stats[player_stats.Pos != "LDT"].reset_index(drop=True)

Step 2: Observations over time¶

The next category we will look at is year. We want our predictors for future seasons to be as accurate as possible, so having data from many seasons will give us more inputs to improve predictive accuracy. However, what if the way the game is played has changed in the last 15 years and the numbers pass-rushers were putting up in 2006 are substancially different than 2020? To measure the change in these statistics over time, we can use a line plot.

a) Isolate Necessary Data¶

For this section we only need the data regarding our independent variable (year), and our dependent variables (Sacks, tackles, and QB hits).

In [30]:
yearly_data = player_stats[['year','Sk','Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits']]

b) Reformat data to prepare for plotting¶

For this plot, we are going to look at mean values rather than all the points at once. There are too many players to each have as one line each in a plot, so looking at the average should make it easier for us to draw conclusions. Additionally, as we want to gain an understanding of general trends in the data over time, the mean will be particualrly useful for us.

To format the data to fit our needs, we need to first group the data by year, then calculate the mean of each column for each year.

In [31]:
yearly_avg =  yearly_data.groupby('year').mean()

Because the plotting method uses the column headers as the labels for each line, we will reformat the columns to have headers more easily readable on a plot. Additionally, we will create a list of colors to go with each line we plot.

In [32]:
yearly_avg.columns = ["Sacks","Total Tackles","QB Hits"]
colors = ['red','blue','green']

d) Plot data¶

To plot a line plot on a dataframe using all the columns, we can simply call plot.line on the object itself. Set the title and axes to the proper size and descriptions. Add a legend to the plot to help identify the lines.

In [33]:
yearly_avg_plot = yearly_avg.plot.line(figsize=(15, 12), fontsize=15, linewidth=3.0)
yearly_avg_plot.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize=20)
yearly_avg_plot.set_ylabel('Quantity', fontsize=20)
yearly_avg_plot.set_title("Average Statistics for Pass Rushers by Year, 2006-2020", fontsize = 30)
yearly_avg_plot.legend(loc=6, prop={'size': 25})
yearly_avg_plot.grid()

d) Analysis¶

The biggest takeaway from the plot above is that the slope of all three lines is almost 0. Over the 15 year span, the average number of tackles for a pass rusher decreased from 48 to 42. Average number of QB hits increased from 11 to 13. Average Sacks stayed at about 5. That means the average of these statistics has remained largely unchanged from season to season. This is good news! We can now be confident that the data from as far back as 2006 can be useful in predicting stats for future seasons.

Step 3: Observations based on Player Age¶

Finally, we want to see how our variables differ based on the age of the player. NFL teams want to have players "in their prime." But when exactly is that? At what age do pass rushers hit their peak on average? Here we hope to find out. We will start by plotting averages by age like above, and see what we can gain from the visualization.

a) Isolate necessarty data¶

For this section we only need the data regarding our independent variable (player age), and our dependent variables (Sacks, tackles, and QB hits). We may want to look at whether or not a team made the pro bowl, so we will include those variables as well.

In [34]:
age_stats = player_stats[['Age','Sk','Tackles_Comb','Tackles_QBHits','made_pro_bowl']]

d) Analysis¶

Average tackles started off under 40, reached almost 47 at age 25, and then decreased from there. Neither average sacks or QB hits changed much, but they both also had their highest points at age 25. This suggests that age 25 is the peak year for players on average, but to be sure, we should look further into the data.

b) Reformat data to prepare for plotting¶

As the line plots of averages did not tell us enough about the trends by age, we will look instead to the distribution. Additionally, it might be useful to differentiate between the average NFL player and the top. It is possible that the best players in the league have their best seasons earlier or later than average. Therefore, for this batch of plots, we will separate the points by whether or not the player was in the pro bowl. This time, to measure distribution, we will use box plots.

First, we group the data into pro-bowl and not pro-bowl players. We will further split into the different variables during the plotting process. As we will be making plots side by side, we need to make sure the axes for the plots are equal. To do this we find and store the max value for each variable to use as the max of the y-axis.

In [109]:
age_data = age_stats.dropna().groupby('made_pro_bowl')

For this plot, we are going to produce a series of subplots- three rows of two columns. The rows are for each of the dependent variables. The left column shows the statistics for players not in the pro bowl, the the right column is for pro bowlers. Additionally, it would be useful to see how Chase Young stacks up against other players in his age group. Chase Young's data will be represented by a red point on top of the box plot.

d) Analysis¶

These plots have a lot to tell us about the data. First, we can confirm that age 25 seems to be the peak age for nfl players. For both pro bowl and non-pro bowl players, average sacks and QB hits were at their highest at age 25. Tackles was highest at age 22, but age 25 also had an above average mean score among the different ages.

We also can confirm that pro bowl players had much better stats than regular players. Across the board, pro bowl players did better than non for every age group in every category. We can also see that the age range of pro bowlers is lower than normal, with the oldest pro bowler on our record being 35, while there were 38 year old non-pro bowlers. That shows players could only remain competitive at an elite level for so long.

There are also several observations to make about Chase Young. At age 21, Young is the youngest pro bowler in our record (no pun intended). That may be an indication that he really is a truly elite talent. However, upon further review, his elite status may be put in doubt. Among non-pro bowl stats, Chase Young fell above average in every category, not just for his age group, but for every individual age group. However, he was more than a standard deviation above average in only the sacks category, putting into question just how dramatically he was setting himself above the pack. Looking at his stats among pro bowlers, things get even worse. In every category and every age, Chase Young was below average. He was even more than a standard deviation below in all categories' ages except tackles, 31-35. These observations enhance the worry that he may not be as elite as people have had me believe.

In the next section we will learn how to make predictions using the data to see what the numbers think are in store for Chase Young's career.

Part 3: Making Predictions¶

Now that we have developed an understanding of that data we have available to us, it is time to start making predictions from it. There are two types of predictors we will be looking at: regression analysis and classification. Regression analysis takes data over a continuous independent variable and finds a predictive trend to estimate an output. Classification prediction systems look at inputted estimators and return which category your input should fall under.

To predict how successful Chase Young's career will be, we want to be able to predict what his stats will look at by age 25, the standard peak season for pass rushers (regression). We then want to make predictors for what an all-pro and pro-bowl season looks like (classification). Finally, we will input Chase Young's predicted stats into the pro-bowl and all-pro predictors to see if his stats should be good enough to earn those titles.

Step 1: Regression Analysis¶

Here we will try to learn what Chase Young's stats will be in each of the three major categories based on age: sacks, QB hits, and tackles. We learned above that making the pro bowl changes the spread of data, so we will include that statistic in our regression model. As recieving an award suggests a different statistic for that season, we can also assume making the all-pro team is also a valid predictor. However, as we want to use these stats to determine whether or not Chase Young will earn these awards in his age 25 season, we cannot use them on a year-by-year basis. Instead, we need to modify them to hold whether or not the player ever made the pro bowl or all pro.

We make that adjustment here:

In [40]:
ever_won = player_stats
group_by_players = player_stats.groupby('Player')
for i in range(len(ever_won)):
    ever_won.at[i, 'made_pro_bowl'] = 1 if group_by_players.get_group(
        ever_won.at[i, 'Player'])['made_pro_bowl'].unique().mean() > 0 else 0
    ever_won.at[i, 'made_all_pro'] = 1 if group_by_players.get_group(
        ever_won.at[i, 'Player'])['made_all_pro'].unique().mean() > 0 else 0

As we learned, the peak season for a player, on average, is at age 25, with stats decreasing on average after that year. Therefore, we will only use statistics from players up to age 25 for our regression model.

In [41]:
under_25 = ever_won.loc[player_stats['Age'] <= 25].reset_index(drop=True)

To prepare the estimators for the regression model, we need to add the proper columns to the dataframe. We need columns for:

  • Age
  • Made the pro bowl
  • Made the all-pro team
  • Age * made the pro bowl
  • Age * made the all-pro team
In [42]:
age_pro_bowl = []
age_all_pro = []

    age_all_pro.append(under_25.at[i, 'Age'] * under_25.at[i, 'made_all_pro'])

As shown by the coefficient of determination, the model is not very accurate, unfortunately. For pro bowlers, the tackle category is the only one where age 25 does not have the highest average.

Step 2: Classification Analysis¶

In this step, we will use decision trees to determine whether or not a given player should be in the pro bowl and on the all-pro team based on their stats for the given season. Once these algorithms are created, we can use them to determine what honors Chase Young's age 25 season should earn.

First, we create our table to use for fitting our decision tree. We need to remove Chase Young from the analysis, as we want to predict him later. If the algorithm already knows the outcome of his exact numbers, then our test would be irrelevant. Additionally, the fitting function for decision trees does not handle missing data well, so we will remove rows that have missing data from the predictor.

In [61]:
classification = player_stats.loc[player_stats['Player'] != 'Chase Young'].dropna()

Next, we set our dependent variables...

According to the accuracy score, the decision tree could only determine whether or not a player made the pro bowl correctly 66.56% of the time, which is far from perfect. Part of the reason this model is not too accurate could be the lack of independent variables. Our table originally held many more data points than we explored in this tutorial, and if we perhaps used more of those to make the prediction, it could have been more accurate. Additionally, pro-bowl selection is somewhat biased. A large weight of pro-bowl selection is taken by fan voting, which potentially makes earning a spot on the pro bowl roster a popularity contest rather than a simple check of the statistics.

Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, we learned how to scrape data from an HTML page. We learned how to organize and standardize a data table. We found different ways to visualize data through plotting. Through the plots, we developed a better understanding of data analysis. Finally, we created linear regression and categorical predictive models, and applied them to test our hypothesis.

But what did we learn about our subject in all these tests? Through our several predictive algorithms, we managed to make a hypothetical "best season" for Washington NFL superstar Chase Young, and then test that best season in our "will he be an all-pro?" predictive algorithm. Unfortunately for all Washington fans reading this tutorial, our best season for Young did not make the cut for all-pro honors. If our tests are to be believed, then my worst fears have been realized: Chase Young is an overhyped player, given high projections more for his charisma and high draft position than for the actual numbers he racked up on the field.

However, there are many reasons to doubt the conclusions we made. First, we look at our algorithms themselves. Unfortunately, they were not very accurate. Our regression tests in particular failed to have a coefficient of determination above even 0.5. That means we should have very little faith in the numbers we made for him. Additionally, because we had so few all-pro seasons to help fit our categorical algorithm, it is possible it also struggled with making accurate predictions. As this is a data science tutorial more than anything, we chose to focus on a very narrow set of statistics to explore. This is a primary reason why our predictive algorithms were so weak.

If we were to return to further analyze and refine our algorithms, we would add many more predictors. These include several of the statistics we left behind in our initial dataframe, including types of tackles and fumbles. It is also possible that team has an effect. Maybe a successful team brings more attention to its players, and therefore makes them more likely to earn honors. A final category I would consider adding was mentioned earlier: draft position. While where one was drafted may not make a difference to the all-pro selection committee, it would be reasonable to assume that a 1st round player would take a bigger step forward by their age 25 season than someone who was never drafted.

However, no matter the refinement, we would never be able to create a completely accurate prediction. Much of what gets a player on the pro-bowl or all-pro team lies outside of statistics. Pro bowl selection is largely voted on by the fans, making popularity a big factor, drowning out raw numbers. While fans do not have a hand in all-pro selection, those honors are still bestowed by human beings rather than a machine learning algorithm, allowing subjective thought to enter the equation.

But it is not only how players are chosen that adds a level of subjectivity to the equation. An important factor includes intangibles; leadership, charisma, hustle. Players can be great not just by their own individual numbers, but by how they bring out the best in their teammates. It is in these intangibles that Washington fans can have hope for a legendary future for Chase Young. He is already a proven leader. He was already named team captain in his rookie season, taking a leadership position over men nearly twice his age. He has charisma in spades; watch his celebrations on the sidelines, or take note of his spectacular nickname, "The Predator." And there are few players with the hustle of Chase Young. Take this play against the Cincinnati Bengals. In terms of the stats we were observing, this is nothing more than one tackle. However, in the context of the game, it was monumental. Young managed to run across the entire field to stop a one yard run on fourth and goal, forcing a fumble and preventing a touchdown. This was a game changing play, even though all it did was tick his tackle count up a notch. Plays like these are what give Young his claim to fame.

Overall, while Washington fans reading this tutorial may be disappointed that Young's numbers have not stood out so far, there is still hope that he may one day become an all-time great. But, as our tutorial shows, a Washington fan should not be more than cautiously optimistic, and should never get carried away by the hype.
